Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: The core challenge in source code summarization lies in capturing long-range dependencies across syntactically and semantically distant tokens, especially in large functions or complex control structures. While Paper 1 highlights the superiority of relative over absolute position encodings in Transformers for this task, it treats relative positions at a single granularity—typically token-level distances. However, source code exhibits hierarchical and structural patterns (e.g., blocks, loops, function calls) where relationships are not uniformly distributed across linear sequences. Drawing inspiration from Papers 2 and 3, which emphasize multi-view and multi-granularity reasoning through contrastive alignment, I propose a novel approach that extends relative positioning into *multi-granular* space. Instead of encoding only how many tokens apart two elements are, my idea models their relative positions across multiple levels of abstraction—such as within a statement, across statements in a block, across function scopes, or even across AST subtree depths. This enables the model to learn when to attend based on structural proximity rather than mere sequential distance. Unlike prior work that uses contrastive learning for view consistency (Paper 2) or reasoning paths (Paper 3), this idea applies multi-granular relative positioning as an enhanced inductive bias within the self-attention mechanism itself. It is not merely about integrating views but enriching the attention computation with structured positional awareness. This differs fundamentally from existing methods by introducing a hierarchy-aware relative position embedding scheme trained to align contextual relevance across granularities via consistency objectives. The result is a more nuanced attention pattern that can dynamically prioritize structurally meaningful dependencies, significantly improving long-range modeling without increasing computational complexity quadratically.

New Idea: ```json{
  "Idea": "This paper proposes Multi-Granular Relative Position Representations (MGRPR) for Transformer-based source code summarization, aiming to enhance the modeling of long-range dependencies by encoding relative positions at multiple levels of syntactic and semantic granularity. Traditional relative position encodings consider only the linear offset between token pairs (e.g., +3 or -5), which fails to capture higher-order structural relationships inherent in code, such as nesting depth, scope boundaries, or control flow hierarchies. MGRPR introduces a layered position representation system that simultaneously models relative positions at four distinct granularities: (1) Token-level (standard relative distance), (2) Statement-level (position relative to start/end of statements), (3) Block-level (e.g., within same loop or conditional), and (4) AST-path-level (depth difference in abstract syntax tree). These multi-granular signals are projected into low-dimensional embeddings and fused into the self-attention weights via additive bias terms. To ensure coherence across granularities, we introduce a consistency regularization loss inspired by contrastive learning: positive pairs are token relations consistently classified across granularities (e.g., both indicating 'nested'), while negative pairs reflect conflicting interpretations. This encourages the model to develop a unified understanding of structural proximity. During training, these representations allow the model to distinguish whether two distant tokens are far due to irrelevant separation or meaningful nesting—critical for accurate summarization. For example, variables used inside deeply nested loops may be dozens of tokens apart but semantically tightly coupled; MGRPR captures this through shared block and AST-level proximity. We evaluate our method on three benchmark datasets (CodeSearchNet, Concode, and JavaDoc) using BLEU, ROUGE-L, and METEOR metrics. Ablation studies confirm the individual contribution of each granularity, while attention visualization shows improved focus on functionally related code segments. By integrating structural awareness directly into the attention mechanism, MGRPR offers a lightweight yet powerful enhancement over standard Transformers, achieving state-of-the-art performance in code summarization with minimal overhead.",
  "Title": "Multi-Granular Relative Position Representations for Modeling Long-Range Dependencies in Source Code Summarization",
  "Experiment": "We implement MGRPR on top of a base Transformer architecture used in source code summarization. First, we preprocess code using a parser (e.g., Tree-sitter) to extract token sequences along with statement boundaries, block delimiters (e.g., braces), and AST paths. For each token pair (i,j), we compute four relative position types: (1) linear offset (j-i), (2) statement-relative offset (e.g., same/different statement, position within), (3) block membership (same loop/condition?), and (4) AST depth difference and lowest common ancestor level. Each type is mapped to a learnable embedding table. In self-attention, these embeddings are summed and added to the attention logits before softmax. The model is trained end-to-end with a dual objective: standard sequence-to-sequence loss and a consistency loss that pulls together embeddings of the same relation across granularities and pushes apart conflicting ones. We use AdamW optimizer, batch size 64, and train on 8 GPUs for 100k steps. Baselines include vanilla Transformer, RPE-only, and AST-aware models like GraphCodeBERT. Evaluation includes automatic metrics (BLEU, ROUGE-L, METEOR) and human evaluation on summary fluency and correctness. We also conduct ablation on each granularity and analyze attention maps to assess long-range dependency capture.",
