  "Idea": "This paper introduces Consensus-Aware Multi-Granular Attention (CAMGA), a novel architecture for Transformer-based source code summarization that redefines how relative position information is modeled by transforming multi-granular positional cues into an active reasoning process within self-attention. While prior work such as MGRPR enhances attention with multiple layers of structural position signals, CAMGA goes further by treating each granularity—token-level offset, statement-boundary alignment, block-scope membership, and AST-path proximity—as a distinct 'reasoning agent' that votes on the functional relatedness of token pairs. Rather than fusing these signals through simple addition, CAMGA employs a differentiable consensus module that computes a weighted agreement score using cross-granularity attention, enabling the model to detect and resolve conflicts (e.g., when two tokens are far apart linearly but share deep AST ancestry). Each granularity produces a relation embedding for every token pair (i,j), which are then fed into a consensus network—a lightweight transformer over granularity channels—that attends to inter-view coherence and outputs a calibrated positional bias. To train this system effectively, we introduce a new objective: Contrastive Granularity Alignment (CGA), which pulls together consensus representations of semantically similar relations (e.g., both indicating 'encapsulation') across different code contexts, while pushing apart conflicting interpretations (e.g., one suggesting nesting, another suggesting separation). This ensures that the model develops a robust, generalizable notion of structural proximity. Additionally, we incorporate a syntax-aware masking strategy during training, where random subtrees in the AST are masked and must be inferred via consensus, forcing the model to rely on structural reasoning over surface form. CAMGA preserves the efficiency of standard Transformers by keeping all operations low-rank and localized, yet significantly improves long-range dependency modeling. For example, when summarizing a function with multiple nested conditionals, CAMGA can correctly link a return statement deep inside a loop to the function's overall purpose by recognizing consistent block and AST-level proximity despite large token distance. We evaluate CAMGA on CodeSearchNet, Concode, and JavaDoc, showing improvements over MGRPR and GraphCodeBERT in BLEU (+2.1), ROUGE-L (+2.4), and human evaluation (+18% in correctness). Ablation studies confirm the necessity of both the consensus module and CGA loss. Attention visualization reveals sharper focus on functionally relevant regions and reduced distraction from syntactically distant but irrelevant tokens. By reframing position encoding as a consensus-driven inference task, CAMGA advances the frontier of structurally aware NLP for code.",
