Both Idea 0 and Idea 1 focus on improving relative position representations in Transformers for source code summarization by incorporating multi-granular structural information. However, when assessing novelty against existing literature, we must consider prior work on relative position encoding (Paper 4), structural awareness in code modeling (Paper 5), and multi-granularity in summarization (Papers 1–3).

Paper 4 explicitly highlights that relative position encodings outperform absolute ones in code summarization—this directly motivates both ideas but also establishes that simple relative positional offsets are already known to be beneficial. Paper 5 introduces a structure-induced Transformer using structural clues in self-attention, suggesting that integrating AST or block-level structure into attention mechanisms is an active research direction. However, neither Paper 4 nor Paper 5 proposes modeling *multiple granularities* of relative position simultaneously, nor do they use consensus-based fusion across syntactic levels.

Idea 0 (MGRPR) proposes a multi-granular extension of relative position embeddings with additive fusion and consistency regularization. While this is more sophisticated than standard RPE, the mechanism—adding multiple learned bias terms from different structural views—is conceptually aligned with feature concatenation/fusion approaches seen in other structured NLP models. The ablation and visualization improvements are compelling, but the core idea overlaps in spirit with the "multi-view" structural integration in Paper 5 and could be perceived as an incremental enhancement rather than a paradigm shift.

In contrast, Idea 1 (CAMGA) makes a significantly more novel contribution by reframing multi-granular position modeling as a *consensus-driven reasoning process*. Instead of treating each granularity as a static signal to be summed, it treats them as agents in a differentiable consensus network that dynamically resolves conflicts via cross-granularity attention. This architectural innovation—using a lightweight transformer over granularity channels—is not present in any of the related papers. Furthermore, the proposed Contrastive Granularity Alignment (CGA) loss and syntax-aware masking strategy introduce new training paradigms tailored to structural generalization, going beyond mere representation fusion.

The leap from MGRPR-style addition to CAMGA’s consensus-based inference represents a clear conceptual and technical advancement. No paper in the provided list explores such a meta-reasoning mechanism over structural views, making Idea 1 substantially more novel and suitable for a top-tier conference contribution.

